      "question": "Assertion (A): If a polynomial $p(x) = x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3$ is divided by $g(x) = x^2 - 2$, then the degree of the remainder $r(x)$ is $1$. \nReason (R): According to the division algorithm for polynomials $p(x) = g(x)q(x) + r(x)$, the degree of the remainder must always be strictly less than the degree of the divisor $g(x)$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Perform polynomial division of $x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3$ by $x^2 - 2$.",
          "The quotient is $x - 3$ and the remainder is $7x - 9$.",
          "The degree of the remainder $7x - 9$ is $1$.",
          "Since the degree of the divisor $g(x) = x^2 - 2$ is $2$, and $1 < 2$, the division algorithm holds.",
          "Both A and R are true, and R explains A."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = (x^2 - 2)(x - 3) + (7x - 9) \\\\ \\text{Degree}(r(x)) = 1 \\\\ \\text{Degree}(g(x)) = 2 \\\\ 1 < 2 \\text{ is true.}$"
      },
